1
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:46,295
Now, after years in the making,
Robert Altman brings to the big screen...

2
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:52,301
count 'em...
24 of your very favorite stars!

3
00:00:52,428 --> 00:00:55,054
David Arkin, Barbara Baxley...

4
00:00:55,180 --> 00:00:57,181
Ned Beatty in Nashville!

5
00:00:57,307 --> 00:01:00,143
And the fabulous performances
of Karen Black, Ronee Blakley...

6
00:01:00,269 --> 00:01:02,186
Timothy Brown in Nashville!

7
00:01:02,312 --> 00:01:05,273
Along with the spectacular
Keith Carradine, Geraldine Chaplin...

8
00:01:05,399 --> 00:01:07,358
with Robert DoQui in Nashville!

9
00:01:07,484 --> 00:01:11,028
And the exciting appearances
of Shelley Duvall, Allen Garfield...

10
00:01:11,155 --> 00:01:12,947
and Henry Gibson in Nashville!

11
00:01:13,073 --> 00:01:16,075
And the fantastic Scott Glenn,
Jeff Goldblum...

12
00:01:16,201 --> 00:01:18,244
Barbara Harris in Nashville!

13
00:01:18,370 --> 00:01:21,539
Not to mention the terrific
David Hayward, Michael Murphy...

14
00:01:21,665 --> 00:01:23,666
Allan Nicholls in Nashville!

15
00:01:23,792 --> 00:01:25,752
And the all-time great Dave Peel...

16
00:01:25,878 --> 00:01:28,838
Cristina Raines,
Bert Remsen in Nashville!

17
00:01:29,006 --> 00:01:31,090
Plus the incredible Lily Tomlin...

18
00:01:31,216 --> 00:01:33,760
Gwen Welles
and Keenan Wynn in Nashville!

19
00:01:33,886 --> 00:01:36,763
Be the first on your block
to marvel at the magnificent stars...

20
00:01:36,889 --> 00:01:39,098
through the magic of stereophonic sound
and living-color picture...

21
00:01:39,224 --> 00:01:42,351
right before your very eyes
without commercial interruption.

22
00:01:42,519 --> 00:01:44,270
Fellow taxpayers...

23
00:01:44,396 --> 00:01:46,856
and stockholders in America...

24
00:01:47,024 --> 00:01:49,400
on the first Tuesday
in November...

25
00:01:49,526 --> 00:01:53,488
we have to make some vital decisions
about our management.

26
00:01:53,614 --> 00:01:56,032
Let me go directly
to the point.

27
00:01:56,158 --> 00:01:58,868
I'm for doing some replacing.

28
00:01:58,994 --> 00:02:01,078
I've discussed
the Replacement Party...

29
00:02:01,205 --> 00:02:03,289
with people
all over this country...

30
00:02:03,415 --> 00:02:06,542
and I'm often confronted
with the statement...

31
00:02:06,668 --> 00:02:09,462
"I don't want
to get mixed up in politics"...

32
00:02:09,588 --> 00:02:12,924
or "I'm tired of politics,"
or "I'm not interested."

33
00:02:14,218 --> 00:02:18,262
Almost as often someone says,
"I can't do anything about it anyway."

34
00:02:19,681 --> 00:02:22,058
Let me point out two things.

35
00:02:22,184 --> 00:02:24,060
Number one:

36
00:02:24,186 --> 00:02:26,896
All of us are
deeply involved with politics...

37
00:02:27,022 --> 00:02:29,023
whether we know it or not...

38
00:02:29,149 --> 00:02:31,651
and whether we like it or not.

39
00:02:31,777 --> 00:02:33,444
And number two:

40
00:02:33,570 --> 00:02:36,614
We can do something about it.

41
00:02:36,740 --> 00:02:39,325
When you pay more
for an automobile...

42
00:02:39,451 --> 00:02:42,995
than it cost Columbus to make
his first voyage to America...

43
00:02:43,121 --> 00:02:45,289
that's politics.

44
00:05:18,735 --> 00:05:22,113
- That girl down there.
- Hold it! Hold it, everybody.

45
00:05:22,239 --> 00:05:23,906
Honey, you gotta
get her out.

46
00:05:24,032 --> 00:05:25,324
- Bob.
- Yes, sir.

47
00:05:25,450 --> 00:05:26,993
I want to talk to Buddy.

48
00:05:27,119 --> 00:05:29,328
Buddy?

49
00:05:29,454 --> 00:05:30,871
Y-Yes, sir, Dad?

50
00:05:30,998 --> 00:05:34,250
Buddy, who is that woman
in there with the hat on?

51
00:05:34,376 --> 00:05:38,087
- She a friend of yours?
- Mr. Hamilton, I'm Opal.

52
00:05:38,213 --> 00:05:40,798
I'm from the BBC, and I'm doing
a documentary on Nashville.

53
00:05:40,924 --> 00:05:43,884
You know I don't allow no people
visitin' when I'm recording.

54
00:05:44,011 --> 00:05:46,095
I want no recording equipment
in that studio.

55
00:05:46,221 --> 00:05:47,930
- Buddy, escort the lady out.
- Yes, sir.

56
00:05:48,056 --> 00:05:51,976
If she wants a copy of this record,
she can buy it when it's released.

57
00:05:52,102 --> 00:05:55,104
No, darling, I'm sorry.
No strangers at all.

58
00:05:55,272 --> 00:05:57,606
Mr. Hamilton,
I'll be waiting outside for you.

59
00:05:57,733 --> 00:05:59,817
We'll have a little interview.

60
00:05:59,943 --> 00:06:02,486
I want to do another one.
Jimmy, you count off.

61
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:04,447
I want to hear
a little more Haven in this one.

62
00:06:09,453 --> 00:06:10,745
Ah, there we are.

63
00:06:10,871 --> 00:06:12,955
This is Studio B right here.

64
00:06:13,123 --> 00:06:15,791
- They're doing some gospel.
- Oh, how sweet!

65
00:06:15,917 --> 00:06:18,919
A recording of some sort.
Glenn, how are you?

66
00:06:19,046 --> 00:06:21,255
- Mind if we sit in?
- Come on in.

67
00:06:21,381 --> 00:06:22,590
It's so little!

68
00:06:22,716 --> 00:06:25,593
We'll be going down front
so we'll get out of their way.

69
00:06:25,719 --> 00:06:29,221
It's so pretty! I've been
to all the recording studios in London.

70
00:06:29,347 --> 00:06:31,891
They're always enormous
and very impersonal.

71
00:06:32,017 --> 00:06:33,642
This is so cozy.

72
00:06:33,769 --> 00:06:36,187
- Keep down so they can...
- Yes, of course.

73
00:06:36,313 --> 00:06:37,980
So they can see
what's going on.

74
00:06:38,106 --> 00:06:39,940
There we are.

75
00:06:43,403 --> 00:06:45,988
This is a choir...
a black choir...

76
00:06:46,114 --> 00:06:49,158
from part of...
from Fisk University here in town.

77
00:06:49,326 --> 00:06:50,868
Good Lord!

78
00:06:50,994 --> 00:06:53,162
- The lady singing is...
- Is she a missionary?

79
00:06:53,330 --> 00:06:55,831
No, she's not.
She's a gospel singer.

80
00:06:55,999 --> 00:06:58,751
She's the wife
of our attorney.

81
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:02,922
I was making
a documentary in Kenya...

82
00:07:03,048 --> 00:07:06,175
and there was this marvelous
woman who was a missionary.

83
00:07:06,343 --> 00:07:08,886
That's why I asked.
She was sensational.

84
00:07:09,012 --> 00:07:11,722
She was converting Kikuyus
by the dozens.

85
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:14,850
She was trying to convert Masais.
Of course, they were hopeless.

86
00:07:15,018 --> 00:07:17,311
I mean, they have
their own sort of religion.

87
00:07:39,668 --> 00:07:42,128
Look at that.
That rhythm is fantastic.

88
00:07:45,048 --> 00:07:46,882
You know, it's funny.
You can tell...

89
00:07:47,008 --> 00:07:50,177
It's come down in the genes
through ages and ages...

90
00:07:50,303 --> 00:07:52,388
and hundreds of years,
but it's there.

91
00:07:52,514 --> 00:07:54,390
Take off those robes...

92
00:07:54,558 --> 00:07:57,726
and one is in... in...
in darkest Africa.

93
00:07:57,853 --> 00:08:01,397
I can just see
their naked, frenzied bodies...

94
00:08:01,523 --> 00:08:03,899
dancing to the beat of...

95
00:08:04,067 --> 00:08:05,901
Do they carry on
like that in church?

96
00:08:06,069 --> 00:08:07,695
Depends on which church
you go to.

97
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:47,318
Hold it, everybody.

98
00:08:47,444 --> 00:08:49,278
Damn it, Bob.

99
00:08:50,697 --> 00:08:53,157
What's the name
of the piano player, Bob?

100
00:08:53,283 --> 00:08:56,952
- That's Frog.
- "That's Frog." He plays like a frog.

101
00:08:57,078 --> 00:08:59,496
We'll try it again.

102
00:09:01,208 --> 00:09:04,543
Jimmy, you count off.

103
00:09:42,707 --> 00:09:45,709
- Damn it to hell!
- Hold it, everybody.

104
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:49,588
- Bob.
- Yes, sir?

105
00:09:49,714 --> 00:09:52,383
What did you say
the piano player's name was?

106
00:09:52,509 --> 00:09:54,802
- Frog.
- Yeah.

107
00:09:54,928 --> 00:09:57,888
When I ask for Pig, I want Pig.

108
00:09:58,014 --> 00:10:01,850
Now, you get me Pig, and then
we'll be ready to record this here tune.

109
00:10:01,977 --> 00:10:04,895
Yes, sir.

110
00:10:08,191 --> 00:10:11,610
You get your hair cut.
You don't belong in Nashville.

111
00:10:31,756 --> 00:10:33,716
This is Bill Jenkins
on special assignment...

112
00:10:33,883 --> 00:10:35,926
for Channel Two News
here at Metro Airport.

113
00:10:36,052 --> 00:10:37,928
We are awaiting
the arrival of Barbara Jean...

114
00:10:38,054 --> 00:10:40,931
who has been away for treatment
at the Baltimore Burn Center.

115
00:10:41,057 --> 00:10:44,184
Already, prior to her arrival,
around 3,000 Barbara Jean fans...

116
00:10:44,311 --> 00:10:46,228
and supporters are here.

117
00:10:46,396 --> 00:10:49,648
They are being held inside
the terminal by security police.

118
00:10:49,774 --> 00:10:53,193
Ma'am, excuse me.
Am I late for Barbara Jean's plane?

119
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:56,739
- I don't think so, but they're
not gonna let you out there.
- Thank you, ma'am.

120
00:10:56,865 --> 00:11:00,492
Members of the Chamber of Commerce
and other fans are on the way.

121
00:11:00,618 --> 00:11:04,246
Also, it's reported Haven Hamilton
will make an appearance here.

122
00:11:04,372 --> 00:11:07,708
There is no question about being involved.

123
00:11:07,834 --> 00:11:10,794
The question is,
what to do?

124
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:12,921
It is the very nature
of government...

125
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:15,382
to strain at a gnat
and swallow a camel.

126
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:19,595
As loyal citizens,
we accept our take-home pay...

127
00:11:19,721 --> 00:11:22,056
understand
most of the deductions...

128
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:25,517
and even, to a degree,
come to expect them.

129
00:11:25,643 --> 00:11:29,355
However, when a government
begins to force its citizens...

130
00:11:29,481 --> 00:11:31,231
to swallow a camel...

131
00:11:31,358 --> 00:11:35,152
it's time to pause
and do some accounting.

132
00:11:35,278 --> 00:11:37,613
Her plane has touched down.
It's down the taxiway...

133
00:11:37,781 --> 00:11:40,240
and will be turning
onto the ramp area...

134
00:11:40,367 --> 00:11:42,951
directly here in front of us
at Metro Airport.

135
00:11:43,078 --> 00:11:45,412
Could you pass me
the crackers, please?

136
00:11:45,538 --> 00:11:47,456
- There you go.
- Thank you.

137
00:11:54,214 --> 00:11:55,756
- Miss, may I have...
- Hi!

138
00:11:55,882 --> 00:11:57,800
A caramel sundae, please?

139
00:11:57,926 --> 00:11:59,718
Honey, we ain't got
no caramel sundae.

140
00:11:59,844 --> 00:12:02,971
- Butterscotch?
- We ain't got no butterscotch sundae.

141
00:12:05,433 --> 00:12:08,018
- Got a strawberry.
- Strawberries are always in season.

142
00:12:08,144 --> 00:12:10,270
Fine, fine.

143
00:12:10,397 --> 00:12:13,023
- That's fine. Thank you.
- Good for you too.

144
00:12:13,149 --> 00:12:17,069
Thank you. Then I'll have
a strawberry sundae, if I may.

145
00:12:17,195 --> 00:12:19,488
- You got it.
- Thank you.

146
00:12:19,614 --> 00:12:22,241
- Sueleen, did you see what he did?
- One strawberry sundae!

147
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:24,368
Did you see
what he just did?

148
00:12:24,494 --> 00:12:27,371
He took the thing off the salt
and threw it up in the air.

149
00:12:27,497 --> 00:12:29,123
Why'd you do that?

150
00:12:29,249 --> 00:12:31,750
What are you doin'
in Nashville?

151
00:12:31,876 --> 00:12:33,836
- Oh, I live here.
- You do?

152
00:12:34,003 --> 00:12:36,713
Hey, fellas, come here.
I want you to see somethin'.

153
00:12:36,840 --> 00:12:39,216
My wife and I...

154
00:12:39,342 --> 00:12:42,177
- My wife is sick, unfortunately.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

155
00:12:42,303 --> 00:12:45,139
Oh, it's just one of those things
that happens.

156
00:12:45,265 --> 00:12:47,975
- Happens in the best of families.
- Yeah.

157
00:12:48,101 --> 00:12:51,019
I wrote me this real hot song.
You wanna hear it?

158
00:12:51,187 --> 00:12:53,355
It's called
"I Never Get Enough."

159
00:12:53,481 --> 00:12:55,899
Okay, listen. All right?

160
00:13:19,841 --> 00:13:23,635
At any moment, Barbara Jean will be
stepping out and will be greeted...

161
00:13:23,761 --> 00:13:27,639
by the Chamber of Commerce,
as well as Mr. Sperry.

162
00:13:27,765 --> 00:13:31,560
Mr. Sperry making his way
to the aircraft now with a big wave.

163
00:13:31,728 --> 00:13:35,063
Of course, he's the president
of Barnett Enterprises.

164
00:13:35,190 --> 00:13:37,065
- We'll be talking with Mr. Sperry...
- How you doin'?

165
00:13:42,030 --> 00:13:43,739
John Triplette?

166
00:13:45,408 --> 00:13:48,076
- You looking for me? I'm John Triplette.
- Oh!

167
00:13:48,244 --> 00:13:50,120
- How are you?
- Hey, John. How are you?

168
00:13:50,246 --> 00:13:53,415
Those kids
in those uniforms are terrific.

169
00:13:53,541 --> 00:13:55,375
- Hello.
- What's your name?

170
00:13:55,502 --> 00:13:59,254
- Del Reese. I'm sorry. Forgive me.
- Thanks for coming out.

171
00:13:59,380 --> 00:14:01,715
- It's a great idea.
- You mean the girls in the costumes?

172
00:14:10,141 --> 00:14:12,518
Barbara Jean's
still on the aircraft. We'll be awaiting...

173
00:14:15,688 --> 00:14:18,065
Thousands of people
have turned out at Metro Airport...

174
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:20,609
to greet Barbara Jean
on her arrival.

175
00:14:20,777 --> 00:14:23,946
Haven Hamilton has just arrived,
typically dressed in white...

176
00:14:24,072 --> 00:14:27,699
his white Jeep being driven
today by his son, Bud.

177
00:14:27,825 --> 00:14:31,161
Members of the Chamber of Commerce
are going over to meet Haven Hamilton.

178
00:14:31,287 --> 00:14:34,122
He's greeting some of his old friends,
business acquaintances.

179
00:14:34,249 --> 00:14:36,458
Autograph seekers are now
making their way over.

180
00:14:36,626 --> 00:14:38,877
Barbara Jean still
is aboard the aircraft...

181
00:14:39,003 --> 00:14:41,505
- Hello, Martha.
- Hi.

182
00:14:41,631 --> 00:14:44,174
- How are you, Martha?
- I'm okay, but, uh...

183
00:14:44,300 --> 00:14:47,261
- Pardon me?
- Listen, uh, I've changed my name.

184
00:14:47,387 --> 00:14:50,472
- Okay.
- It's L.A. Joan from now on.

185
00:14:50,640 --> 00:14:52,432
Let me get some cigarettes.

186
00:14:52,559 --> 00:14:54,351
Your Aunt Esther wants to see you.

187
00:14:54,477 --> 00:14:57,271
- She's in the hospital...
- Wait a minute.

188
00:14:57,397 --> 00:14:59,815
- And she'd like to see...
- This guy's a rock star. Hang on.

189
00:15:02,151 --> 00:15:05,320
Can I get your autograph?
You're Tom, aren't you?

190
00:15:05,446 --> 00:15:06,989
Tom, Bill, and Mary?

191
00:15:07,156 --> 00:15:09,533
Jesus, you ought to stop that diet
before you ruin yourself.

192
00:15:09,659 --> 00:15:13,662
Do you believe this? They have
our album here. Hey, how's it selling?

193
00:15:13,788 --> 00:15:15,789
- What's that?
- Bill, Mary, and Tom.

194
00:15:15,915 --> 00:15:17,916
A little slow,
but we sell mostly country.

195
00:15:18,042 --> 00:15:21,795
I'm the handsome one in the front.
I don't have my glasses on
in the picture, but I...

196
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:25,924
Wait a minute! Hal Phillip Walker
looks exactly like Connie White.

197
00:15:32,015 --> 00:15:35,684
Now, Del, I like...
I like the idea of bands.

198
00:15:35,810 --> 00:15:38,312
I want you to listen
to those little kids, honey.

199
00:15:38,438 --> 00:15:40,397
I want you to know
they practiced...

200
00:15:40,523 --> 00:15:42,524
every day after school
for two hours...

201
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:44,401
for a whole month
just for this event.

202
00:15:44,527 --> 00:15:46,236
- Yes, that's so nice.
- Isn't that cute?

203
00:15:46,362 --> 00:15:48,530
I think that'll cheer her up.
Pearl, shut up.

204
00:15:48,698 --> 00:15:52,618
- Just like your mama, son.
- Yes, yes, I'm sure he is.

205
00:15:52,744 --> 00:15:55,829
... tragically burned
in an accident involving a fire baton.

206
00:15:55,955 --> 00:15:58,707
She has now fully recovered.
However, she's required to take...

207
00:15:58,833 --> 00:16:01,543
- Excuse me, Barnett.
- I got no time right now!

208
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:03,295
Jesus!

209
00:16:03,421 --> 00:16:05,881
I just think they're so cute,
Buddy.

210
00:16:06,049 --> 00:16:08,383
Hello, hello. Testing.
I wonder if this thing's on.

211
00:16:08,509 --> 00:16:11,386
Hey, wait. Are you Tom
of Bill, Mary, and Tom?

212
00:16:11,554 --> 00:16:13,347
- Yeah. What's your name?
- Jamie.

213
00:16:13,473 --> 00:16:15,891
You thought of voting
for Walker for president?

214
00:16:16,059 --> 00:16:19,311
- I don't vote for nobody.
- Oh, come on.

215
00:16:19,437 --> 00:16:21,563
Just read it.
He's got a fantastic platform.

216
00:16:21,731 --> 00:16:24,608
How you doin', Sarge?
Ya kill anybody this week?

217
00:16:27,570 --> 00:16:30,072
Did you ever see
such pretty girls in your life?

218
00:16:30,198 --> 00:16:33,033
Someday you're gonna be
big girls like your mommies...

219
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:36,203
and you're gonna be lookin'
for a nice, young, handsome man.

220
00:16:36,329 --> 00:16:38,330
Come on, Buddy.
You say hello.

221
00:16:38,456 --> 00:16:41,583
My son Buddy, he just graduated
from Harvard Law School...

222
00:16:41,709 --> 00:16:44,836
and we're tryin' to give him
all the breaks we never got.

223
00:16:44,962 --> 00:16:47,130
- Buddy, say hello to the people.
- Hi.

224
00:16:47,256 --> 00:16:49,758
Thank you, Buddy.

225
00:16:49,926 --> 00:16:53,595
And thank you again for comin' here
and makin' us all feel so at home.

226
00:16:58,976 --> 00:17:01,812
Here she comes!
Our Barbara Jean!

227
00:17:03,606 --> 00:17:06,608
Come on.
Get on the other side.

228
00:17:06,734 --> 00:17:09,778
Here's our own Barbara Jean!

229
00:17:09,946 --> 00:17:11,488
May I have a word, Barnett?

230
00:17:11,614 --> 00:17:14,282
None of that shit.
Come on. Come on.

231
00:17:14,409 --> 00:17:16,034
Get up there.
Come on.

232
00:17:16,160 --> 00:17:18,328
Who do you think
you are? Marlon Brando?

233
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:20,747
Barbara Jean, ladies and gentlemen!

234
00:17:20,873 --> 00:17:24,251
- Hi!
- Ah, look at that!

235
00:17:25,545 --> 00:17:29,089
Thank you so much.
Hi, sweetie, darling!

236
00:17:32,135 --> 00:17:34,886
Hi, Bill. Hi, Mary.
Where's Tom?

237
00:17:35,012 --> 00:17:36,805
- Take my bag?
- Sure.

238
00:17:36,931 --> 00:17:39,850
- You were supposed
to meet us at the gate.
- Then let's go meet at the gate.

239
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:42,436
- Norman, let's go to the limo.
- The limo is just outside.

240
00:17:43,521 --> 00:17:45,981
Barbara Jean, for you.

241
00:17:46,149 --> 00:17:48,358
- Thank you, Haven.
- Right here for the photographer.

242
00:17:48,484 --> 00:17:51,653
Thank you, Tennessee Twirlers,
for coming out today...

243
00:17:51,821 --> 00:17:54,239
and thank you,
Franklin High School Band.

244
00:17:54,365 --> 00:17:57,075
I think you kids
get better every year.

245
00:18:24,604 --> 00:18:28,315
Oh, little beauty!
Thank you so much!

246
00:18:28,441 --> 00:18:31,234
Are you gonna ride into town
with me or not?

247
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:34,738
Go on without me. I'm gonna wait,
'cause I think she's gonna sing.

248
00:18:34,864 --> 00:18:38,033
Her? She ain't gonna sing.
She don't sing unless she get paid.

249
00:18:39,035 --> 00:18:40,660
I'd like to thank you...

250
00:18:40,787 --> 00:18:43,371
for coming out
to greet me today.

251
00:18:43,539 --> 00:18:46,458
It's great to be home.
It's hot as a firecracker.

252
00:18:48,461 --> 00:18:50,378
What's so funny about that?

253
00:18:50,546 --> 00:18:53,089
Me and the boys are gonna be
out at the Opry this week...

254
00:18:53,216 --> 00:18:55,759
and like my granddaddy
always used to say...

255
00:18:55,885 --> 00:18:58,762
if you're down to the river,
I hope you'll drop in.

256
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:01,181
Oh! Yes, that's sweet.

257
00:19:01,307 --> 00:19:03,308
Who writes your material, darlin'?

258
00:19:04,477 --> 00:19:07,187
Barnett, who are
all those people inside?

259
00:19:07,313 --> 00:19:10,440
It's just airport security,
'cause of all the hijackers.

260
00:19:10,566 --> 00:19:13,652
- Did they come to see me?
- They can see you pretty good.

261
00:19:13,778 --> 00:19:16,571
Then I'd like to go in
and say hello.

262
00:19:16,697 --> 00:19:18,615
I believe
Barbara Jean wants to go inside...

263
00:19:18,741 --> 00:19:21,701
- Barnett, I'm sorry, darlin'.
- To see the fans who were not able...

264
00:19:21,828 --> 00:19:23,703
to make it out here.

265
00:19:23,830 --> 00:19:26,873
This was a little bit unscheduled.
She's on her way down there...

266
00:19:26,999 --> 00:19:30,418
probably to greet
some fans inside there.

267
00:19:30,586 --> 00:19:34,881
- Stepping down the walkway with Barnett.
- Watch out for the water.

268
00:19:35,007 --> 00:19:37,092
Right behind, Haven Hamilton...

269
00:19:37,218 --> 00:19:40,011
and all the other friends,
members, and, uh...

270
00:19:40,137 --> 00:19:42,264
She's fallen! Harold, come on!

271
00:19:42,431 --> 00:19:44,182
She's fallen somewhere
down there.

272
00:19:44,308 --> 00:19:47,060
If we can get down there...
if we have enough cable.

273
00:19:47,186 --> 00:19:50,272
Don't know how far
we can make it.

274
00:19:50,398 --> 00:19:53,775
Who do you think is running Congress?

275
00:19:53,901 --> 00:19:56,945
Farmers? Engineers?
Teachers? Businessmen?

276
00:19:58,281 --> 00:20:01,992
No, my friends.
Congress is run by lawyers.

277
00:20:02,118 --> 00:20:05,620
A lawyer is trained for two things
and two things only:

278
00:20:05,788 --> 00:20:07,873
To clarify... that's one...

279
00:20:07,999 --> 00:20:11,251
And to confuse...
that's the other thing.

280
00:20:11,377 --> 00:20:15,422
He does whichever
is to his client's advantage.

281
00:20:15,548 --> 00:20:18,425
Did you ever ask a lawyer
the time of day?

282
00:20:18,551 --> 00:20:21,261
He told you how to make
a watch, didn't he?

283
00:20:21,387 --> 00:20:25,265
Ever ask a lawyer how to get
to Mr. Jones's house in the country?

284
00:20:25,391 --> 00:20:27,809
You got lost, didn't you?

285
00:20:27,935 --> 00:20:31,813
Congress is composed
of 535 individuals.

286
00:20:32,982 --> 00:20:35,775
Two hundred and eighty-eight
are lawyers.

287
00:20:35,902 --> 00:20:40,030
And you wonder
what's wrong in Congress.

288
00:20:40,156 --> 00:20:42,991
No wonder we often know
how to make a watch...

289
00:20:43,117 --> 00:20:45,827
but we don't know
the time of day.

290
00:20:45,995 --> 00:20:49,748
No wonder it takes six or seven years...

291
00:20:55,379 --> 00:20:57,339
What the hell
is the matter with you?

292
00:21:09,644 --> 00:21:13,104
Yes, I'm talking about replacement.

293
00:21:13,230 --> 00:21:16,524
Replacing this lawyeristic,
red-taped...

294
00:21:16,651 --> 00:21:18,693
and blank-taped government...

295
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:21,488
with the yes-and-no language
of farmers and teachers...

296
00:21:21,614 --> 00:21:23,698
engineers and businessmen.

297
00:21:23,866 --> 00:21:25,951
I'm not pessimistic
about this country.

298
00:21:26,077 --> 00:21:29,037
She finally collapsed here
on the sidewalk. Sort of a faint.

299
00:21:29,163 --> 00:21:32,165
That's all we've been able
to determine at this moment.

300
00:21:32,291 --> 00:21:35,293
We interviewed Mr. Sperry.
He said the same thing.

301
00:21:35,419 --> 00:21:37,587
Haven Hamilton
said the same thing as well.

302
00:21:37,713 --> 00:21:40,674
That's about it for the moment
from Metro Airport.

303
00:21:40,800 --> 00:21:44,010
For Channel Two News,
this is Bill Jenkins reporting.

304
00:21:44,136 --> 00:21:46,471
Let's consider our national anthem.

305
00:21:46,597 --> 00:21:48,556
Nobody knows the words.

306
00:21:48,683 --> 00:21:50,767
Nobody can sing it.

307
00:21:50,893 --> 00:21:53,103
Nobody understands it.

308
00:21:58,526 --> 00:22:00,402
Yee-haw!

309
00:22:07,743 --> 00:22:11,204
I suppose
all the lawyers supported it...

310
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:13,707
because a lawyer
wrote the words...

311
00:22:13,833 --> 00:22:15,875
and a judge wrote the tune.

312
00:22:16,002 --> 00:22:17,335
Careful, Buddy.

313
00:22:17,461 --> 00:22:19,754
- Read it carefully.
- Watch out for that truck.

314
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:22,757
And I say "read it"
because I know you can't sing it.

315
00:22:22,883 --> 00:22:27,137
Read all four verses, and you'll
understand what I'm talking about.

316
00:22:27,263 --> 00:22:30,724
Yes, sir, I would support work
and vote for replacement.

317
00:22:30,850 --> 00:22:35,437
- Change our national anthem back
to something people can understand...
- This is terrific, Norman.

318
00:22:35,604 --> 00:22:39,607
Back to something that would make
a light shine in their faces.

319
00:22:39,734 --> 00:22:43,069
Hey, man, get off my car!
Don't lean on my car!

320
00:22:43,195 --> 00:22:46,823
I just got this goddamn thing fixed,
so don't lean on it.

321
00:22:46,949 --> 00:22:50,702
Oh, Jesus Christ. Oh, God.

322
00:22:50,828 --> 00:22:52,787
Hey, man,
get the hell off my car!

323
00:22:52,913 --> 00:22:54,914
You almost made me fall!

324
00:22:55,041 --> 00:22:58,126
Great, thanks.
Can I have one too?

325
00:22:58,294 --> 00:23:01,004
Thanks a lot. Just keep those
cards and letters comin' in, folks.

326
00:23:01,130 --> 00:23:03,965
- I feel faint.
- I'm gonna get us a Popsicle.

327
00:23:04,133 --> 00:23:06,009
Just a minute. Hello?

328
00:23:06,135 --> 00:23:08,803
- All those mangled bodies.
- Would you go to that Popsicle truck...

329
00:23:08,929 --> 00:23:10,972
and get us a couple sweet ices?

330
00:23:11,098 --> 00:23:15,185
There must be 20 cars piled up,
one on top of the other,
some of them upside-down.

331
00:23:15,311 --> 00:23:17,353
- Come on.
- I saw a leg sticking out.

332
00:23:17,480 --> 00:23:21,274
This is gonna be a mess.
I don't know how long it...

333
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:24,486
Can you just pull on through
where the ambulance went?

334
00:23:24,612 --> 00:23:26,488
You want to try it?

335
00:23:26,614 --> 00:23:28,698
- What's the matter, son?
- It's stalled.

336
00:23:28,824 --> 00:23:31,993
- What did you want? Popsicle?
- I wish my cameraman had been here.

337
00:23:32,161 --> 00:23:35,622
He's never around. I need something
like this for my documentary.

338
00:23:35,748 --> 00:23:37,707
I need it.
It's... It's America.

339
00:23:37,833 --> 00:23:39,751
Those cars
smashing into each other...

340
00:23:39,877 --> 00:23:41,836
and all those
mangled corpses...

341
00:23:41,962 --> 00:23:43,213
Just a minute.
Just a minute.

342
00:23:47,343 --> 00:23:49,427
Well, it's hard to really say.

343
00:23:49,553 --> 00:23:51,554
You see...

344
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:54,849
after they opened her up, they figured
they ought to do an exploratory.

345
00:23:55,017 --> 00:23:57,227
You know,
give her kind of an overhaul.

346
00:23:57,353 --> 00:23:59,187
- Twenty dollars?
- Twenty dollars.

347
00:23:59,355 --> 00:24:03,066
- I'll give you five.
- No, I'll take 15.

348
00:24:03,192 --> 00:24:05,235
You'll take 15?
I'll give you ten.

349
00:24:05,361 --> 00:24:08,029
I can think
of no sensible reason why New York...

350
00:24:08,155 --> 00:24:11,407
must of necessity have 12,000...

351
00:24:11,534 --> 00:24:13,409
major crimes committed...

352
00:24:13,536 --> 00:24:16,871
for every 1,000
committed in Tokyo.

353
00:24:18,124 --> 00:24:20,708
- Excuse me.
- Yet these are the true victims.

354
00:24:22,461 --> 00:24:26,339
Some very funny notions
have developed in American politics.

355
00:24:26,465 --> 00:24:28,299
Um, let me see.

356
00:24:28,425 --> 00:24:30,552
Um, have you any children?

357
00:24:30,678 --> 00:24:33,888
Yes, I have two children.
I have a boy and a girl.

358
00:24:34,014 --> 00:24:36,891
Oh, isn't that nice!
How old are they?

359
00:24:37,059 --> 00:24:38,935
Twelve and 11.

360
00:24:39,061 --> 00:24:41,312
Do they want to be singers
like their mummy?

361
00:24:42,398 --> 00:24:44,732
Um, well,
my children are deaf.

362
00:24:47,570 --> 00:24:49,445
They're... They are deaf.
They were born deaf.

363
00:24:49,572 --> 00:24:51,573
Oh, my God, how awful!

364
00:24:51,699 --> 00:24:54,951
- It's so depressing.
- Now, just a minute. That's not so.

365
00:24:55,077 --> 00:24:58,037
- I wish you could see my boy.
- Oh, I couldn't.

366
00:24:58,164 --> 00:25:00,790
- He has the most incredible personality.
- It's the sadness of it.

367
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:04,794
What happened is, he made
a million dollars on a flyswatter...

368
00:25:04,920 --> 00:25:07,213
because it had
a red dot in the center.

369
00:25:07,339 --> 00:25:09,841
- Flyswatter?
- That's right. Just a red dot.

370
00:25:09,967 --> 00:25:13,011
He was sittin' in a buffet,
and he was eatin'...

371
00:25:13,137 --> 00:25:16,431
and he saw a woman,
and she was swattin' flies.

372
00:25:16,557 --> 00:25:19,017
And, uh, she...
He said...

373
00:25:19,143 --> 00:25:22,228
"What makes
the difference in flyswatters?"

374
00:25:22,354 --> 00:25:25,315
'Cause it has to do
with the Industrial Revolution.

375
00:25:25,441 --> 00:25:29,444
The thing with these country people is
they have a real grassroots appeal.

376
00:25:29,612 --> 00:25:33,239
- Well, hell, they got fans.
- And they're the people
that elect the president.

377
00:25:33,365 --> 00:25:36,492
- We're gonna do everything we can.
- You line up a lot of movie stars...

378
00:25:36,619 --> 00:25:40,538
I think people here feel that
movie stars are eccentric and crazy.

379
00:25:40,664 --> 00:25:42,790
- Communists.
- Well...

380
00:25:42,958 --> 00:25:45,210
- A lot of 'em are.
- It's been said, now.

381
00:25:45,336 --> 00:25:48,796
- Then I want to go to the Grand Ole Opry.
- Forget that.

382
00:25:48,923 --> 00:25:51,549
- 'Cause I have to have my record...
- I don't like music.

383
00:25:51,675 --> 00:25:54,552
- I'm gonna go see what's goin' on.
- I have a gold record...

384
00:25:54,678 --> 00:25:57,931
- and it needs to be signed.
- Get the hell away from my truck!

385
00:25:58,057 --> 00:26:01,517
- Goddamn it! Sons of bitches!
- Shit!

386
00:26:01,644 --> 00:26:04,354
I say, could I please speak
to Mr. Tommy Brown?

387
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:06,940
- What?
- I'm sorry.

388
00:26:07,066 --> 00:26:10,109
Is it possible to have a few words
with Mr. Tommy Brown?

389
00:26:10,236 --> 00:26:13,404
I'm from the BBC. I'm doing
a documentary on Nashville.

390
00:26:13,530 --> 00:26:15,490
What is the BBC?

391
00:26:15,616 --> 00:26:17,825
- British Broadcasting Company.
- Oh, English.

392
00:26:17,952 --> 00:26:19,953
It was called
"Wanda, Wander."

393
00:26:20,079 --> 00:26:23,122
No, that song was called
"Wonder, Wanda."

394
00:26:33,008 --> 00:26:35,510
- I don't really know.
- Thank you, thank you.

395
00:26:35,636 --> 00:26:38,012
- Goddamn it, it was "Wanda, Wander."
- It was "Wonder, Wanda."

396
00:26:38,138 --> 00:26:41,808
"Wanda, Wander"! What difference
does it make? It was a hit!

397
00:26:41,934 --> 00:26:44,852
There's no breathing space.

398
00:26:44,979 --> 00:26:47,188
What we need,
first and foremost...

399
00:26:47,356 --> 00:26:49,524
is a commonsense approach.

400
00:26:49,692 --> 00:26:51,526
Nothing complicated.

401
00:26:51,652 --> 00:26:55,405
Is Mr. Brown going to...
Will he be here soon?

402
00:26:55,531 --> 00:26:58,658
Yeah, he's in the back changin'.
He has to put his makeup on.

403
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:01,661
Whenever he's going to have
an interview, he puts his makeup on...

404
00:27:01,787 --> 00:27:04,038
and likes to get
all prettied up, you know?

405
00:27:04,164 --> 00:27:06,040
That's nice.

406
00:27:06,166 --> 00:27:08,042
He must be
a marvelous person...

407
00:27:08,168 --> 00:27:10,878
to have all you lovely people
working for him.

408
00:27:11,046 --> 00:27:14,465
I know the problems in the South.
I mean, I've heard of them.

409
00:27:14,591 --> 00:27:16,759
Well, yeah.

410
00:27:16,885 --> 00:27:20,138
- He's a very liberal guy.
- That's lovely.

411
00:27:20,264 --> 00:27:23,725
By the way, I'd like for you
to meet his wife. This is Joy.

412
00:27:24,768 --> 00:27:26,060
- Mrs. Brown?
- Yes.

413
00:27:36,739 --> 00:27:38,698
Today in America...

414
00:27:38,824 --> 00:27:41,034
with its unmatched resources...

415
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:43,494
it is exceedingly ridiculous...

416
00:27:43,620 --> 00:27:45,997
a total absurdity...

417
00:27:46,123 --> 00:27:48,374
that any citizen with any ailment...

418
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:51,836
mental or physical,
should go medically unattended.

419
00:27:51,962 --> 00:27:53,796
We're settin' up
everything for you.

420
00:27:53,922 --> 00:27:57,467
- We got pictures the right height.
- Oh, the little bird again.

421
00:27:57,593 --> 00:28:00,136
Isn't that beautiful?
I remember when you gave that to me.

422
00:28:00,262 --> 00:28:02,388
I remember I almost threw it out.

423
00:28:02,514 --> 00:28:04,557
Good afternoon, girls.

424
00:28:06,477 --> 00:28:08,853
I'd like you to wait
outside the room a while...

425
00:28:08,979 --> 00:28:12,106
because I know Aunt Esther
would like to fix herself up a little.

426
00:28:12,232 --> 00:28:14,275
I want my dog.
Where is my dog?

427
00:28:18,113 --> 00:28:21,157
- I just need one shot.
- I'm sorry.
- Could you excuse us?

428
00:28:21,283 --> 00:28:24,118
- Come on in, sir.
- How you doin', Howard?

429
00:28:24,244 --> 00:28:25,578
I'm sorry.
No press allowed.

430
00:28:25,704 --> 00:28:27,747
We'll put
these pictures above your head.

431
00:28:27,873 --> 00:28:29,957
- Delbert, I got no time.
- I know.

432
00:28:30,125 --> 00:28:32,126
I just stopped by
to see Barbara Jean.

433
00:28:32,252 --> 00:28:33,836
How you doin'?
How's lawyerin'?

434
00:28:33,962 --> 00:28:36,964
Nobody pays me no mind.
I'm just like another flunky.

435
00:28:37,091 --> 00:28:39,217
- Would you mind crankin' me up?
- More white carnations!

436
00:28:39,343 --> 00:28:41,469
If I told him once,
I told him twice.

437
00:28:41,595 --> 00:28:44,514
Bud, this is a hospital!
This ain't no construction site!

438
00:28:44,640 --> 00:28:47,975
- I am not the press.
- Go build another chair!

439
00:28:48,102 --> 00:28:49,769
Goddamn it!

440
00:28:49,895 --> 00:28:52,188
I am not the press.
I am from the BBC.

441
00:28:52,314 --> 00:28:54,023
Damned if I don't
keep my pledge.

442
00:28:54,149 --> 00:28:58,152
- Look who's here... Mr. Brown.
- Glad you're here, but cut it short.

443
00:28:58,278 --> 00:29:00,321
How do you do?
Nice to see you.

444
00:29:00,447 --> 00:29:03,199
You look as beautiful
as a big, black butterfly.

445
00:29:03,325 --> 00:29:05,785
I'm gettin' jealous.
I'm gettin' jealous.

446
00:29:05,911 --> 00:29:08,621
- You better get out of here.
- He's gettin' mighty jealous.

447
00:29:08,747 --> 00:29:12,291
I gotta sit myself up a bit. Hi.

448
00:29:12,418 --> 00:29:15,169
- I need to talk to you.
- You got it.

449
00:29:15,337 --> 00:29:17,380
All right, everybody.
Doctor's gotta talk turkey.

450
00:29:17,506 --> 00:29:19,757
Barnett, there's somebody
I want you to meet.

451
00:29:19,883 --> 00:29:22,176
- John Triplette from California.
- John Triple?

452
00:29:22,302 --> 00:29:23,845
- Triplette.
- Okay. All right.

453
00:29:23,971 --> 00:29:26,889
- He's a killer.
- Give us some good news.

454
00:29:27,015 --> 00:29:28,850
Excuse us, please.

455
00:29:29,017 --> 00:29:31,352
- Are you a relative?
- What? No, no.

456
00:29:31,478 --> 00:29:35,189
- Can you tell me how she is?
- She's fine. It's her husband
I'm concerned about.

457
00:29:35,315 --> 00:29:38,651
- Now, say somethin' good.
You got two seconds.
- Fair.

458
00:29:38,777 --> 00:29:40,862
- Can I have a light?
- Excuse me?

459
00:29:40,988 --> 00:29:44,449
- Can I have a light?
- Yeah, sure.

460
00:29:44,575 --> 00:29:47,034
The incident you described
just now is very similar...

461
00:29:47,161 --> 00:29:49,370
to what you have here
for your second admission...

462
00:29:49,496 --> 00:29:52,874
- when it was diagnosed as some kind of intestinal disorder.
-  - What's your name?

463
00:29:53,041 --> 00:29:55,042
Bud Hamilton's my name.

464
00:29:55,210 --> 00:29:57,795
Esther's awake,
and she's dying to see you.

465
00:29:57,921 --> 00:30:01,757
I'll be there in a minute, okay?
I'm talking to someone right now.

466
